<paper id="1751556912"><title>Designated Confirmer Signatures and Public-Key Encryption are Equivalent</title><year>1994</year><authors><author org="Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corporation" id="2142935726">Tatsuaki Okamoto</author></authors><n_citation>81</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1494965429</reference><reference>1541330898</reference><reference>1554259298</reference><reference>1568324739</reference><reference>1590696383</reference><reference>1881111533</reference><reference>1882430379</reference><reference>1970606468</reference><reference>1972792640</reference><reference>1979215153</reference><reference>2004881597</reference><reference>2012045293</reference><reference>2015826302</reference><reference>2027528470</reference><reference>2055993618</reference><reference>2074594718</reference><reference>2095708839</reference><reference>2108834246</reference><reference>2117362057</reference><reference>2135740056</reference><reference>2143832005</reference><reference>2151413173</reference><reference>2151433956</reference><reference>2156186849</reference><reference>2911473785</reference></references><venue id="1153524033" type="C">International Cryptology Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-48658-5_8</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.64684">Undeniable signature</keyword><keyword weight="0.43986">Computer security</keyword><keyword weight="0.43498">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.60238">Encryption</keyword><keyword weight="0.42763">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.5318">Public-key cryptography</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer-Verlag</publisher><abstract>The concept of designated confirmer signatures was introduced by Chaum [Cha94] to improve a shortcoming of undeniable signatures. The present paper formalizes the definition of designated confirmer signatures and proves that a designated confirmer signature scheme is equivalent to a public-key encryption scheme with respect to existence. I